[Student "S"]
{With both Majors, the correct response to Stayman is 2\H. Partner now bids 3NT.  

With both Majors, the correct response to Stayman is 2\H. Partner now bids 3NT. 

Partner denies having 4 \Hs so obviously he must hold 4 \Ss. You therefore correct the contract to 4\S, your known 4-4 Major fit.

East plays 4\S. South takes two top \Cs, then leads the \HJ.

Loser List: \S = 1 : \H = 0 : \D = 1 : \C = 2 :: Total = 4

There are lots of possibilities for getting rid of one loser. The \SQ might drop, or she might be in the South hand, finessable. The \Hs might split 3-3, providing for the discard of a \D loser. South might hold the \DQ so that finesse works. 

Suppose you win the \H in your hand and try the \S finesse. If North has the \SQ you will then have to find the \Hs splitting, which is not likely, or the \DQ in the South hand. 

A better plan would be to shun the trump Queen finesse entirely. Play the \SK, then \SA. If the \SQ falls then pull the last trump and you are home free.

If the \SQ DOESN'T fall, play your other two \H winners. When North discards on the last \H you exit with a small trump to a defender's \SQ.  

If South wins the \S you will just have to depend on the \D finesse. But if North takes the trick he will be endplayed, having to give you a ruff/sluff in \Cs, or lead into dummy's \D K J.

This plan combines several chances.}
[Play "W"]CA

